Elastic Load Balancing: the four types.

A single instance has two problems. It dies at three in the morning and your app is down until someone notices. And you can't ship a new version without taking the whole site offline. The fix is to run more than one instance, which immediately raises a question: if there are several instances, how does a user reach the app, rather than picking one instance by its I-P address? That's the job of a load balancer. It accepts incoming connections at a stable D-N-S endpoint and spreads them across a fleet of healthy targets. Along the way, it adds health checks, so unhealthy targets stop receiving traffic; connection draining, for graceful removal mid-deploy; T-L-S termination, so the certificate lives on the load balancer instead of on every instance; and optional stickiness, so a client can return to the same target.

AWS offers four types. The Application Load Balancer, or A-L-B, works at Layer seven. It understands H-T-T-P and H-T-T-P-S and routes on content: path, host, header, query, or method. The Network Load Balancer, or N-L-B, works at Layer four. It moves T-C-P and U-D-P packets without parsing them, giving a static I-P per availability zone, millions of requests per second, and a preserved client source I-P. The Gateway Load Balancer, or G-W-L-B, works at Layer three, inserting third-party appliances like firewalls and intrusion-detection systems transparently inline. And the Classic Load Balancer is legacy, only for old migrations.

The exam decision is almost always this: A-L-B for H-T-T-P, and N-L-B for everything else. The next sections drill into each one.
